#Overview

Petri Net Chomper (pn-chomper) is a browser game where the map is a #Petri Net.
Tokens are the player's chomping icons. Transitions are doorways. Places
are rooms. Arcs are corridors. The game is intended as casual fun
and as a teaching tool for Petri net concepts.

The key insight driving this design is that #Petri Net semantics already define
the movement rules. A token moves from a place through an enabled transition
into one or more output places — that is exactly what a game character does
when walking through a doorway into a room. When a transition has multiple
output arcs the token splits, creating two chompers. When a transition has
multiple input arcs, tokens from several places merge to fire it. These are
the game's movement mechanics, not abstractions bolted on.

##Architecture

The game is built in TypeScript and runs in the browser with no server.
Source is organised as notlob modules, one concept per file.

Module map (addresses are notlob module paths):

- #Petri Net     — core data model (places, transitions, arcs)
- #Petri Marking — token distribution and firing semantics
- #Game Map      — built-in maps as Petri net definitions
- #Game State    — live game state (token positions, score, ghosts)
- #Game Engine   — game loop, input handling, win/lose detection
- render/canvas  — canvas renderer, HUD, and all game entities
- #IO PNML       — PNML export and import; external nets load via `?map=` URL
- game/main      — entry point, wires modules together

##Game Mechanics

Chompers are tokens. Each one lives in a Place. On each turn the player
selects an enabled transition adjacent to one of their tokens; that token
fires through the transition and arrives in the output place(s). Token
distribution and enabling are tracked by #Petri Marking. If the transition
has two output arcs, a new token is born — the player gains a chomper. Dots
in places are eaten on entry. The #Game Engine drives the game loop and ghost
AI. The live GameState — score, token positions, dot state — is held in #Game State.
Ghosts are autonomous tokens that fire enabled transitions at random.

Each built-in level is a GameNet value defined in #Game Map. External Petri
nets can be loaded via importPNML from #IO PNML, either from a local file
or via a `?map=` URL.

##Petri Net as Pedagogy

Because the map is a real Petri net, the game teaches:
- What a place is (a room / location)
- What a transition is (a doorway / event)
- What an arc is (a corridor / dependency)
- What enabling means (can you go through this door?)
- What firing means (going through the door)
- Token splitting (one chomper becomes two)
- Token merging (two chompers must converge to fire a shared transition)

##Future Ideas

- Soundness checking: highlight dead transitions (blocked corridors)
- Coloured tokens: different chomper types with different abilities
- Data guards: doorways that only open when you carry certain items (variables)
- Export fired sequence as an event log (process mining hook)

